KPP Stem Tracking : Progress 27 May 2014

JH MC, TB - TLL C - Calibre ML - SWI GS, TH, NM - Tui

Aims

  • determine what is causing the partially poor correlation between stem velocity and average log velocity and fix it
  • understand the log tool 'night shift' issue and fix it
  • understand when a stem will be matched via stemNumber to a good USNR image file

Things Done or In Progress

  • Calibre PC being unplugged. FIXED. Power to PC hardwired.

  • Primary pneumatic actuator performance sensitive to air temperature. Failing to perform properly at night when the temperature low. FIXED 2/4/14. Actuator now being heated with electric coil. Further improvements will include dynamically adjusting timing parameters based on actual actuator performance. UPDATE 23/5/2014: The mic failed and the tool was down for a few weeks. It has now been repaired and upgraded (see chung email)

  • Stem sonic tool vs hitman. 10/3/2014. See separate report.

  • GS/TH made changes to the code that operates on stem sonic info coming from foxtrot and inserts stem velocity into the SWIPC database

  • Stem velocity written to SWIPC not matching the velocity written to Foxtrot log file (WeekNN_YY.txt). PARTIALLY FIXED as of 5pm 31/3/2014.

  • Log records being written to SWIPC database with different log numbers and sonic velocities but duplicate position and shape data. FIXED 25/3/2014.

  • GS has been in touch with USNR re the stem shape image filename issue (the number used is the previous stemNumber+1 which is ok when the previous stem had a stemNumber with the same number of digits as the current, but is otherwise wrong.) USNR can fix the problem, but to do so requires a software upgrade theat MarkC needs to approve.

Default Stem SWV

When a good sonic value is available for a stem, then: (a) the stem is assigned a 4-digit stem number (b) the measured tem SWV is written to the SWIPC database

When no good stem sonic result is available: (a) the stem gets assigned a 5-digit stem number (b) a default value for the stem velocity is assigned based on where the stem came from and this value is written to the SWIPC database

If the above is correct then:

Why do so many of the 4-digit stems (i.e. stems with good meausred SWV) seem to be being assigned default SWV's?

Why, as shown in the next plot, do stems from the same 'forest' with no good SWV measured not all have the same assigned SWV?

How do any of the 5-digit stems get random post-PLC velocities?

Duplicate Log Records

Are there still duplicate log records in the SWIPC database?

/* find stemID's of stems with duplicate logs */
select top 10 
  l1.stemID, 
  l1.ID, 
  l2.ID, 
  l1.DateAndTime 
from 
  phase2 as l1, 
  phase2 as l2 
where 
  l1.stemID=l2.stemID 
  and l1.Startpos=l2.Startpos 
  and l1.ID<l2.ID 
order by 
  l1.ID desc

Datum Classification

Consider a model for the sonic data that involves two processes:

  1. a linear relationship between stem swv and average log swv, but with a large amount of noise coming from
  1. measurement error
  2. not having all of the stem represented by logs
  3. physical differences between the resonance of the whole stem and the average of its parts
  1. a process for which stem and average log velocities are uncorrelated, but whose pdf matches the marginal distribution.

Process 2 might originate in the stem instrument (hardware or software) or might result from a stem tracking failure.

How can we classify data points according to which of these processes they originated by?

Ransac

Robustly fit a linear relationship using a RANSAC atype algorithm. Inliers belong to porcess 1, outliers to process 2.

plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-17

This model suggests ~35% of time the stem sonic velocity is essentially uncorrelated with the average log sonic speed.

This mixture regression modelling works well enough that it can be used from here on to quantify improvements.

USNR

What fraction of the stems have binfiles written using the wrong ID?

select 
  count(*)
from (
  select 
    stemID, 
    min(DateAndTime) as DateAndTime, 
    max(stemNumber) as stemNumber, 
    min(m_fail) as m_fail 
  from 
    phase2
  where 
    (m_fail is not null or m_nslices is not null) 
    and DateAndTime>'2014-05-01'
  group by 
    stemID
  ) as tmp
 where 
   m_fail like '%binfile does not%'

40%!

Things That Could Be Done

  • Fix whatever casues the foxtrot log file to record multiple records for some stems

  • insert both stem swv from foxtrot (unmodified) and stem swv post PLC (the same as going to the optimizer) into the SWIPC database.

  • capture a large number of time series from foxtrot and reanalyse for odd results - if reanalysis better correlates with log avg then less reason to chase mismatches (need KPP sonics Sytem password)

  • collect a larger hitman v KPP stem sonic dataset to further investigate if the random noise originates in the stem tool (hardwar or software), and to clarify if the tool needs to be completely rebuilt or just re-engineered to sucessfully hit a higher % of stems.

  • why is the year part of the WeekXX_YY.txt log files on foxtrot greater than the current year by 1? (i.e. log files from 2014 are named WeekXX_15.txt)

  • Assign a unique stemID at time each stem processed (rather than retrospectively via XXX.py) - actually this must be being done already in the echo db

  • Rationalize the various data repositories (echo db, CUR_STEM_DET.dbf, bucketCaliper.csv, SWIPC db, ...) and automate reporting

from questions.md:

  • Compare the stem-to-log velocity model in use in the bucker with other implementations

  • Check that the model used to predict log velocity from stem velocity would not benefit from incorporating more data. Investigate continually updating the model based on data collected, would this improve the bucking optimiser?

  • What are the log velocity grade limits?

  • Where does the 'Forest' information come from? Is it reliable?

  • Understand the differences between final log LED/SED and LED/SED from the bin files. Is this solely due to error in the final log diameter measurement? Ifso, what's a reasonable tolerance (50mm tolerance rejects >40% of logs)

  • Record full grade numbers rather than 3char codes (e.g. S30R rather than DS3)
